{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600649"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:06:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:06:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15625"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15625"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.56,0,0.16,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8316"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70626"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8316"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56091"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"7004"},{"type":"tags","id":"10109"},{"type":"tags","id":"10581"},{"type":"tags","id":"10592"},{"type":"tags","id":"10632"},{"type":"tags","id":"10640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20069"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70626"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProlactin is a hormone produced by the anterior pituitary gland. Its secretion is primarily controlled by inhibitory signals from the hypothalamus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a cause of hyperprolactinaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Growth hormone excess","Dopamine antagonist medications","Hyperthyroidism","Hypogonadism","Cushing syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETonic dopaminergic secretion from the hypothalamus is primarily responsible for the inhibition of prolactin synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDopamine antagonist medications\u003C/strong\u003E are therefore a common cause of hyperprolactinaemia as they block this pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common causes of hyperprolactinaemia include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedications (especially dopamine antagonists like antipsychotics)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysiological (pregnancy, lactation)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPituitary tumours (e.g. prolactinomas)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypothalamic-pituitary stalk disruption\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth hormone excess\u003C/strong\u003E does not directly cause hyperprolactinaemia. \u003Cstrong\u003EHyperthyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ECushing syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E are not direct causes of hyperprolactinaemia, though they may coexist with conditions that do cause elevated prolactin levels. \u003Cstrong\u003EHypogonadism \u003C/strong\u003E(and resultant infertility) and galactorrhoea are the sequelae of hyperprolactinaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prolactin secretion is primarily inhibited by tonic dopaminergic signalling from the hypothalamus","Common causes of hyperprolactinaemia include medications, pregnancy, and pituitary tumours","Growth hormone excess does not directly cause hyperprolactinaemia"],"references":["Samperi I, Lithgow K, Karavitaki N. Hyperprolactinaemia. J Clin Med. 2019;8(12):2203. Published 2019 Dec 13. doi:10.3390/jcm8122203","Al-Chalabi M, Bass AN, Alsalman I. Physiology, Prolactin. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507829/","Fukuhara N, Nishiyama M, Iwasaki Y. Update in Pathogenesis, Diagnosis, and Therapy of Prolactinoma. Cancers (Basel). 2022 Jul 24;14(15):3604. doi: 10.3390/cancers14153604. PMID: 35892862; PMCID: PMC9331865","Dai C, Kang J, Liu X, Yao Y, Wang H, Wang R. How to Classify and Define Pituitary Tumors: Recent Advances and Current Controversies. Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2021 Mar 17;12:604644. doi: 10.3389/fendo.2021.604644. PMID: 33815274; PMCID: PMC8010908","Lenders NF, Earls PE, Inder WJ, McCormack AI. The evolution in pituitary tumour classification: a clinical perspective. Endocr Oncol. 2023 Apr 21;3(1):e220079. doi: 10.1530/EO-22-0079. PMID: 37434652; PMCID: PMC10305559","Yatavelli RKR, Bhusal K. Prolactinoma. [Updated 2023 Jul 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459347/","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56091"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15625"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56091"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T12:27:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T12:28:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8316"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70626"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"descr